properties.Notes: This 109-acre marine park has 5,600-feet of shoreline on Henderson Bay and includes Cutts Island which half mile from shore and reachable only by boat. It provides scenic views of sunsets, the Olympic Mountains & Puget Sound.

properties.Name: Alta Vista Trail
properties.Trail: Trail Length: 1.1 mi; Trail Surface: Paved
properties.Notes: This trail through the Paradise Meadows is a great place to view wildflowers.
properties.Source: Location contributed by Mt. Rainier National Park

properties.Name: Indian Bar Trail
properties.Trail: Trail Length: 7.7 mi;  Top Elevation: 5914 ft; Trail Surface: Paved
properties.Notes: This is a unique section of the Wonderland Trail along miles of ridge, through subalpine meadows, with views of the southeast side of Mount Rainier. It ends in a broad green valley into which pour a dozen waterfalls.
properties.Source: Location contributed by Mt. Rainier National Park

properties.Name: Burroughs Mtn Trail
properties.Trail: Trail Length: 2.4 mi; Elevation Gain: 900 ft; Trail Surface: Natural/Soft Surface
properties.Notes: The mountain views from any point on this trail are superb and Burroughs Mountain offers possibly the finest, most assessable tundra in the Cascades.
properties.Source: Location contributed by Mt. Rainier National Park

properties.Name: Chenuis Falls Trail
properties.Trail: Trail Length: 0.2 mi; Trail Surface: Natural/Soft Surface
properties.Notes: This short trail to the Chenuis Falls crosses the Carbon River on foot logs.
properties.Source: Location contributed by Mt. Rainier National Park

properties.Name: Chinook Pass to Tipsoo Lake Trail
properties.Trail: Trail Length: 0.2 mi; Trail Surface: Natural/Soft Surface
properties.Notes: This trail is part of the Naches Peak Loop Trail - one of the most popular trails in the park.
properties.Source: Location contributed by Mt. Rainier National Park

properties.Name: Comet Falls-Van Trump Trail
properties.Trail: Trail Length: 2.8 mi; Elevation Gain: 900 ft; Trail Surface: Natural/Soft Surface
properties.Notes: Three hundred-twenty foot Comet Falls is a popular destination for many hikers. Look for marmots, pikas, and goats on rocky open slopes. From the falls, you can continue to Van Trump Park for spectacular views of peaks and glaciers.
properties.Source: Location contributed by Mt. Rainier National Park

properties.Name: Crystal Lakes Trail
properties.Trail: Trail Length: 3 mi; Elevation Gain: 2300 ft; Trail Surface: Natural/Soft Surface
properties.Notes: By late July and early August the meadows explode with a wide variety of colorful subalpine wildflowers. Watch for elk and mountain goats grazing on the surrounding slopes and ridges anytime throughout the summer and early fall.
properties.Source: Location contributed by Mt. Rainier National Park

properties.Name: Deadhorse Creek Trail
properties.Trail: Trail Length: 1.1 mi; Trail Surface: Paved
properties.Notes: This trail through the Paradise Meadows provides glacier views.
properties.Source: Location contributed by Mt. Rainier National Park

properties.Name: Denman Falls Trail
properties.Trail: Trail Length: 0.3 mi; Trail Surface: Natural/Soft Surface
properties.Notes: Take this short loop trail for a look at Denman Falls.
properties.Source: Location contributed by Mt. Rainier National Park

properties.Name: Eastside Trail
properties.Trail: Trail Length: 10.1 mi; Trail Surface: Natural/Soft Surface
properties.Notes: This trail connects the subalpine highlands of Chinook Pass with the deep, lowland forests of the Ohanapocosh area. Hikers can walk the entire route or access shorter sections for a day hike.
properties.Source: Location contributed by Mt. Rainier National Park

properties.Name: Emmons Moraine Trail
properties.Trail: Trail Length: 3 mi; Elevation Gain: 700 ft; Trail Surface: Natural/Soft Surface
properties.Notes: This moderate trail follows the Glacier Basin trail for one mile and then goes left along the moraine.
properties.Source: Location contributed by Mt. Rainier National Park

properties.Name: Shriner Peak Trail
properties.Trail: Trail Length: 4 mi; Elevation Gain: 3434 ft; Trail Surface: Natural/Soft Surface
properties.Notes: Although this trail begins in the forest, it soon climbs into an old burn area that is open and shadeless.  Once on top of the ridge, hikers enjoy commanding views of Mount Rainier, the Ohanapecosh Valley and the Cascades.
properties.Source: Location contributed by Mt. Rainier National Park

properties.Name: Golden Gate Trail
properties.Trail: Trail Length: 0.9 mi; Trail Surface: Natural/Soft Surface
properties.Notes: This short trail through Paradise Park begins and ends at the Skyline Trail, cutting off a loop of the longer trail.
properties.Source: Location contributed by Mt. Rainier National Park

properties.Name: Green Lake Trail
properties.Trail: Trail Length: 5.4 mi; Elevation Gain: 1000 ft; Trail Surface: Natural/Soft Surface
properties.Notes: This trail passes through old growth forest to reach Green Lake. Along the trail, view Ranger Falls. Because of flood damage to the road, the trail begins at the Carbon River Entrance. Bikes are permitted on the part of the trail that follows the road.
properties.Source: Location contributed by Mt. Rainier National Park

properties.Name: Hidden Lake Spur
properties.Trail: Trail Length: 0.5 mi; Trail Surface: Natural/Soft Surface
properties.Notes: This short spur trail off the Palisades Lake Trail goes along the shore of Hidden Lake.
properties.Source: Location contributed by Mt. Rainier National Park

properties.Name: Skyline Trail to Myrtle Falls
properties.Trail: Trail Length: 1 mi; Trail Surface: Natural/Soft Surface
properties.Notes: This trail through the Paradise Meadows is wheelchair accessible with assistance.
properties.Source: Location contributed by Mt. Rainier National Park

properties.Name: Huckleberry Creek Trail
properties.Trail: Trail Length: 7.7 mi; Trail Surface: Natural/Soft Surface
properties.Notes: This lesser known trail starts in the Mount Baker-Snoqualmie National Forest and then enters the northeast corner of the park, is snow-free early in the season and goes through some amazing old growth.
properties.Source: Location contributed by Mt. Rainier National Park

properties.Name: Indian Henry's Hunting Ground via Kautz Creek Trail
properties.Trail: Trail Length: 5.7 mi; Elevation Gain: 3000 ft; Trail Surface: Natural/Soft Surface
properties.Notes: Boulder fields and large standing dead trees are remnants of the Kautz Creek flood of 1947. Indian Henry's, meadows are in full bloom from mid -July through August and fall colors are impressive from mid-September into October.
properties.Source: Location contributed by Mt. Rainier National Park

properties.Name: Carbon Glacier Trail
properties.Trail: Trail Length: 17 mi; Elevation Gain: 1640 ft; Trail Surface: Natural/Soft Surface
properties.Notes: This trail overlaps with the Green Lake and Wonderland Trails. It is open to bicycles until Ipsut Campground (the old Carbon River Road.) Past the road, the trail follows the Carbon River through the forest to the snout of the glacier.
properties.Source: Location contributed by Mt. Rainier National Park

properties.Name: Lake Eleanor Trail
properties.Trail: Trail Length: 3.3 mi; Trail Surface: Natural/Soft Surface
properties.Notes: This trail is a spur off the Northern Loop Trail. It goes through the Grand Park Area to Lake Eleanor.
properties.Source: Location contributed by Mt. Rainier National Park

properties.Name: Mirror Lakes Trail
properties.Trail: Trail Length: 0.6 mi; Trail Surface: Natural/Soft Surface
properties.Notes: This short spur trail leads from the Wonderland Trail to Mirror Lakes.
properties.Source: Location contributed by Mt. Rainier National Park

properties.Name: Moraine Trail
properties.Trail: Trail Length: 0.4 mi; Trail Surface: Natural/Soft Surface
properties.Notes: This short spur takes off from the DeadhorseCreek Trail.
properties.Source: Location contributed by Mt. Rainier National Park

properties.Name: Mount Freemont Trail
properties.Trail: Trail Length: 1.3 mi; Elevation Gain: 900 ft; Trail Surface: Natural/Soft Surface
properties.Notes: This trail, which is accessed from the Sourdough Ridge trail,  traverses the west side of a rocky ridge to a fire lookout built in the 1930s.
properties.Source: Location contributed by Mt. Rainier National Park

properties.Name: Naches Loop Trail
properties.Management: Owner: National Park Service & USFS; Manager: NPS & USFS
properties.Trail: Trail Length: 3.5 mi; Trail Surface: Natural/Soft Surface
properties.Notes: This easy loop is one of the most popular hikes in the park with fields of subalpine flowers  and breathtaking views of Mount Rainier. Late summer and fall brings an abundant supply of huckleberries. Half of the hike is on the Pacific Crest Trail.
properties.Source: Location contributed by Mt. Rainier National Park

properties.Name: Nisqually Vista Trail
properties.Trail: Trail Length: 1.2 mi; Trail Surface: Paved
properties.Sports: Summer Sports: Hiking; Winter Sports: Snowshoeing
properties.Notes: Walk amidst the clouds through high-country meadows on this easy trail. Enjoy excellent views of Mount Rainier and the Nisqually Glacier. In the winter, this route makes a good snowshoe trek.
properties.Source: Location contributed by Mt. Rainier National Park

properties.Name: North Burroughs Mtn Trail
properties.Trail: Trail Length: 0.8 mi; Trail Surface: Natural/Soft Surface
properties.Notes: This short trail connects the Wonderland Trail and the Burroughs Mountain Trail.
properties.Source: Location contributed by Mt. Rainier National Park

properties.Name: North Puyallup Trail
properties.Trail: Trail Length: 2.7 mi; Trail Surface: Natural/Soft Surface
properties.Notes: This trail along the Puyallup River provides access to the Wonderland Trail.
properties.Source: Location contributed by Mt. Rainier National Park

properties.Name: Northern Loop Trail
properties.Trail: Trail Length: 40 mi; Trail Surface: Natural/Soft Surface
properties.Notes: This long loop hike passes through the most pristine wilderness of the park including a cliff of colorful rocks, numerous mountain lakes, and views of Mount Rainier and its glaciers. The southern part of the loop uses the Wonderland Trail.
properties.Source: Location contributed by Mt. Rainier National Park

properties.Name: Owyhigh Lakes Trail
properties.Trail: Trail Length: 3.5 mi; Trail Surface: Natural/Soft Surface
properties.Notes: This hike offer an array of secluded mountain lakes and meadows aglow with wildflowers in mid-summer. The jagged cliffs of Governors Ridge rise high above the lakes to the east while Tamanos Mountain lies directly west.
properties.Source: Location contributed by Mt. Rainier National Park

properties.Name: Palisades Lake Trail
properties.Trail: Trail Length: 3.6 mi; Elevation Gain: 1800 ft; Trail Surface: Natural/Soft Surface
properties.Notes: Although there are no views of Mount Rainier from this trail, hikers can easily spend all day enjoying the array of lakes, wildflowers, or huckleberries in season. Look for pikas and marmots in the talus slopes.
properties.Source: Location contributed by Mt. Rainier National Park

properties.Name: Paul Peak Trail
properties.Trail: Trail Length: 2.9 mi; Trail Surface: Natural/Soft Surface
properties.Notes: This often overlooked trail winds through a mixed old-growth forest and crosses Wonderland Creek before joining the Wonderland Trail.
properties.Source: Location contributed by Mt. Rainier National Park

properties.Name: Rainforest Loop
properties.Trail: Trail Length: 0.3 mi; Trail Surface: Natural/Soft Surface
properties.Notes: Starting across from the Carbon River Entrance Station, this short loop trail takes visitors through a fine example of a temperate rain forest.
properties.Source: Location contributed by Mt. Rainier National Park

properties.Name: Rampart Ridge Trail
properties.Trail: Trail Length: 4.6 mi; Trail Surface: Natural/Soft Surface
properties.Notes: This steep loop trail passes through forests and offers ridge top vistas. Trail is accessed from the Trailof the Shadows.
properties.Source: Location contributed by Mt. Rainier National Park

properties.Name: Silver Forest Trail and Emmons Vista Overlook
properties.Trail: Trail Length: 1 mi; Trail Surface: Natural/Soft Surface
properties.Notes: This trail passes the Emmons Vista Overlook with its spectacular views and then goes through an old burned area. The "silvery" color of the charred trees bleached white by the weather give the area its name.
properties.Source: Location contributed by Mt. Rainier National Park

properties.Name: Skyline Trail
properties.Trail: Trail Length: 5.5 mi; Elevation Gain: 1700 ft; Trail Surface: Natural/Soft Surface
properties.Notes: The trail offers stunning displays of subalpine wildflowers, a close-up look at Mount Rainier and the Nisqually Glacier, and, on a clear day, views of peaks as far south as Oregon's Mount Hood.
properties.Source: Location contributed by Mt. Rainier National Park

properties.Name: Sourdough Ridge Trail and Dege Peak
properties.Trail: Trail Length: 3.4 mi; Trail Surface: Natural/Soft Surface
properties.Notes: Enjoy the beautiful subalpine meadows of the Sunrise area. A gentle climb to the ridge top offers breathtaking views of Mount Rainier, with Mount Baker, Glacier Peak, and Mount Adams in the distance. Stay on trail to protect fragile plants.
properties.Source: Location contributed by Mt. Rainier National Park

properties.Name: Spray-Seattle Park Trail
properties.Trail: Trail Length: 7 mi; Trail Surface: Natural/Soft Surface
properties.Notes: Open forest predominates for most of this hike. Sites include Eagle's Cliff overlook, which offers a spectacular view of Mount Rainier and the Mowich Glacier, and a spur trail that leads to a good view of Spray Falls.
properties.Source: Location contributed by Mt. Rainier National Park

properties.Name: St Andrews Creek Trail
properties.Trail: Trail Length: 2.3 mi; Trail Surface: Natural/Soft Surface
properties.Notes: This trail goes from St Andrews Creek over the Klapatche Ridge to join the Wonderland Trail and Klapatche Park.
properties.Source: Location contributed by Mt. Rainier National Park

properties.Name: Tipsoo Lake Trail
properties.Features: Features: Interpretive Signs, Lake Access, Scenic View
properties.Trail: Trail Length: 0.9 mi; Trail Surface: Natural/Soft Surface
properties.Notes: These trails loop around scenic Tipsoo Lake.
properties.Source: Location contributed by Mt. Rainier National Park

properties.Name: Tolmie Peak Trail
properties.Trail: Trail Length: 1.4 mi; Elevation Gain: 1010 ft; Trail Surface: Natural/Soft Surface
properties.Notes: This trail, accessed from the Wonderland trail, passes through the forest to Eunice Lake, then climbs to the Tolmie Peak fire lookout for views of Mount Rainier. Please stay on the trail to avoid damaging the meadows surrounding the lake.
properties.Source: Location contributed by Mt. Rainier National Park

properties.Name: Trail of the Shadows
properties.Trail: Trail Length: 0.7 mi; Trail Surface: Natural/Soft Surface
properties.Notes: Human and natural history come together in the forest and meadows of Longmire. You'll see a replica of an early homestead cabin and discover the plants and animals that call this area their home.
properties.Source: Location contributed by Mt. Rainier National Park

properties.Name: Twin Firs Loop Trail
properties.Trail: Trail Length: 0.4 mi; Trail Surface: Natural/Soft Surface
properties.Notes: This short trail passes through old growth forest.
properties.Source: Location contributed by Mt. Rainier National Park

properties.Name: Wonderland Trail
properties.Trail: Trail Length: 82.4 mi; Trail Surface: Natural/Soft Surface
properties.Notes: This 93 mile trail encircles Mount Rainier. It is a strenuous hike with lots of elevation gain and loss, through lowland forests and valleys and into high alpine and sub-alpine areas.
properties.Source: Location contributed by Mt. Rainier National Park

properties.Sports: Summer Sports: Camping, Hiking, Horseback Riding
properties.Notes: Tremendous views, great camping and a near-wilderness experience are yours for a short trip up and over the Norse Peak ridge. This trail provides breathtaking vistas of Mount Rainier, Crystal Mountain Basin and Norse Peak Wilderness area.

properties.Sports: Summer Sports: Hiking, Horseback Riding, Mountain Biking

properties.Trail: Trail ID: 1176; Trail Surface: Natural/Soft Surface
properties.Sports: Summer Sports: Fishing, Hiking, Horseback Riding
properties.Notes: This is an easy two- mile hike for all ages through lush moss-laden old-growth forest to Greenwater Lakes, also known as Meeker Lake. Continue five miles to Echo Lake and experience the Norse Peak Wilderness.
